{"parse":{"title":"hound","pageid":36565,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Hound}}\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/haʊnd/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-hound.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊnd|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|en|:inh|enm:hound<ety:inh<ang:hund<id:dog>>>|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|hound}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hund}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hund}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hundaz}}. {{doublet|en|canine}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|nl|hond||dog}}, {{cog|de|Hund||dog}}, {{cog|da,nb,nn,sv|hund||dog}}, {{cog|fo,is|hundur||dog}}.\n\nIn 14th-century England, ''hound'' was the general word for all domestic canines, and {{m|en|dog}} referred to a subtype resembling the modern mastiff and bulldog (much as the distinction between {{m|de|Hund}} and {{m|de|Dogge}} in contemporary German).<ref name=\"dog\">[http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=48370&lang=en]</ref> By the 16th century, ''dog'' had become the general word, and ''hound'' had begun to refer only to breeds used for [[hunt]]ing.<ref>[https://books.google.com/?id=uZcs6poXkfEC&pg=PA215]</ref>\n[[File:Bvdb-bassethound1.jpg|thumb|A [[basset hound|basset '''hound''']].]]\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[dog]], particularly a [[breed]] with a good sense of [[smell]] developed for [[hunt]]ing other animals.\n# Any [[canine]] animal.\n# {{lb|en|by extension}} Someone who [[seek]]s something.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1996|author=Marc Parent|title=Turning Stones|page=93|publisher=w:Harcourt Brace & Company|isbn=0151002045\n|passage=On the way out of the building I was asked for my autograph. If I'd known who the signature '''hound''' thought I was, I would've signed appropriately.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004|author=w:Jodi Picoult|title=w:My Sister's Keeper|publisher={{w|Simon & Schuster}},|isbn=0743486196|page=483\n|passage=I still do not know if he's taken on this case because he's a glory '''hound''', because he wants the PR, or if he simply wanted to help Anna.}}\n# {{lb|en|by extension}} A male who constantly [[seek]]s the company of desirable women.\n#* '''1915''', [[w:Norman Duncan|Norman Duncan]], \"A Certain Recipient\", in [[w:Harper's Magazine|''Harper's'']], volume 122, number 787,<!--sic--> December 1915, republished in ''Harper's Monthly Magazine'', volume 122, December 1915 to May 1916, page 108,\n#*: \"Are you alone, Goodson? {{...}} I thought, perhaps, that the {{...}} young woman, Goodson, who supplanted Mary?\"{{...}}\n#*: \"She had a good many successors, John.\"\n#*: \"You are such a '''hound''', in that respect, Goodson,\" said Claywell, \"and you have always been such a '''hound''', that it astounds me to find you—unaccompanied.\"\n# A despicable person.\n#: {{synonyms|en|cur}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Coriolanus|V|vi|passage=Boy! false '''hound'''!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1888|year_published=|author={{w|Rudyard Kipling}}|title={{w|The Phantom 'Rickshaw and Other Tales}}|chapter=The Phantom Rickshaw|location=Allahabad|publisher=A.H. Wheeler and Co.|page=12|text=I turned away and left her to finish her journey in peace, feeling, but only for a moment or two, that I had been an unutterably mean '''hound'''.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1973|author=w:Elizabeth Walter|title=Come and Get Me and Other Uncanny Invitations\n|passage='You blackmailing '''hound''',' the parrot said distinctly, in what Hodges recognized as General Derby's voice. Anstruther turned pale.}}\n# A [[houndfish]].\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* In more recent times, '''hound''' has been replaced by Modern English '''dog''' but the sense remains the same.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from ''hound''\n|bagel hound|bagle hound|ban-hound|bitch-hound|painted hound|chow hound|coon hound|covert-hound|double-nosed Andean tiger hound|drag hound|drag-hound|hell-hound|publicity-hound|sea hound|swine-hound|hound of hell\n|Afghan hound\n|autograph hound\n|basset hound|African Lion Hound\n|Bavarian mountain hound\n|bearhound\n|bitch hound\n|bloodhound\n|boarhound\n|bookhound\n|boozehound|rough-hound\n|buckhound\n|Bulgarian Hound\n|chowhound\n|coonhound\n|corpse hounds\n|covert hound|pole-hound\n|deerhound|axehandle hound,axhandle hound\n|draghound\n|follow the hounds\n|foxhound\n|Gabriel's hounds\n|gazehound|puddle-hound\n|gorehound\n|grayhound\n|greyhound\n|hare and hounds\n|harehound\n|hell hound\n|hound dog\n|houndfish\n|houndish\n|houndlike\n|houndling\n|houndly\n|hound shark\n|houndsberry\n|houndsman\n|hounds of war\n|hound's tongue\n|houndstooth\n|houndy\n|Hungarian hound\n|Ibizan Hound\n|jizzhound\n|lenshound\n|Lithuanian Hound\n|lyam-hound\n|minkhound\n|newshound\n|nursehound\n|otterhound\n|Otterhound\n|pack hound\n|powder hound\n|publicity hound\n|rock hound\n|{{vern|rough hound}}\n|shag-hound\n|sighthound\n|scent hound\n|sinhound\n|sleuth-hound\n|sleuthhound|beerhound|elkhound|heckhound|hellhound|hounder|houndstongue|powderhound|rumhound|swinehound\n|slot-hound\n|smooth hound\n|smuthound\n|staghound\n|Tyrolean Hound\n|war hound\n|whorehound\n|wolfhound\n}}\n\n{{col3|en|title=Expressions containing ''hound''\n|clean as a hound's tooth\n|hold with the hare and run with the hounds\n|run with the hare and hunt with the hounds\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|dog, hunting dog}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|hond}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|[[كَلْبُ]] [[صَيْد]]|m}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|բարակ}}\n*: Middle Armenian: {{t|axm|զաղառ}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|хрътка|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|獵犬|tr=lièquǎn}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|chrt|m}}, {{t|cs|lovecký pes}}, {{t|cs|honič|m}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|hund|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|hond|m}} {{q|general}}, {{t+|nl|jachthond|m}} {{q|hunting}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|hundo}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|hagijas}}\n* Faroese: {{t+|fo|hundur|m}}, {{t|fo|veiðihundur|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|koira}}, {{t+|fi|hurtta}}; {{t+|fi|metsästyskoira}} {{q|hunting dog}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chien de chasse|m}}, {{t+|fr|braque|m}}, {{t+|fr|molosse|m}}, {{t+|fr|chien courant|m}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{t+|fy|hûn|c}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|braco|m}}, {{t|gl|sabuxo|m}}, {{t|gl|sabuio|m}}, {{t|gl|corricón|m}}, {{t|gl|lebreu|m}}, {{t|gl|acadán|m}}\n* Georgian: {{t+|ka|ძაღლი}}, {{t|ka|მონადირე ძაღლი}}, {{t|ka|ქოფაკი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Hund|m}} {{q|general}}, {{t+|de|Jagdhund|m}} {{q|hunting}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κυνηγόσκυλο|n}}, {{t+|el|λαγωνικό|n}}, {{t+|el|ζαγάρι|n}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|כלב ציד|m|tr=kelev tsáyid}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|श्वान|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|vadászkutya}}\n* Hunsrik: {{t|hrx|Jachthund|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|hundur|m}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|chasohundo}}\n* Irish: {{t+|ga|cú|m}}\n*: Old Irish: {{t|sga|cú|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|bracco|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|猟犬|tr=りょうけん, ryōken}}, {{t+|ja|狩犬|tr=かりいぬ, kariinu}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|’рт|m}}, {{t|mk|загар|m}}\n* Malay:\n*: Jawi: {{t|ms|انجيڠ ڤمبورو}}\n*: Rumi: {{t|ms|anjing pemburu}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kurī whakangau}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|hund|c}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|gończy|m}}, {{t+|pl|ogar|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|[[cão]] [[de]] [[caça]]|m}}, {{t+|pt|sabujo|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t|ro|câine de vânătoare|m}}, {{t+|ro|ogar|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|го́нчая|f}} {{q|соба́ка}}, {{t|ru|охо́тничья соба́ка|f}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t+|gd|cù|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|kȇr|m}}, {{t+|sh|hrt|m}}\n* Sicilian: {{t|scn|cani di caccia|m}}, {{t|scn|cani braccu|m}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|chrt|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|perro de caza|m}}, {{t+|es|sabueso|m}}, {{t+|es|cárabo|m}} {{qualifier|disused}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|hund|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|asong pangaso}}\n* Tibetan: {{t|bo|རྔོན་ཁྱི}}\n* Turkmen: {{t|tk|tazy}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|гонча́к|m}}, {{t|uk|го́нчий собака|f}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|chó săn}}\n* Yiddish: {{t+|yi|הונט|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|any canine animal}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|koiraeläin}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|one who seeks something}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|metsästäjä}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|cazador|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Jäger|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|caçador|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ищейка|f}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|cacciaturi|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|male who constantly seeks the company of desirable females}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|häntäheikki}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|mullereiro}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Schürzenjäger|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mulherengo|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|кобель|m}}\n* Sicilian: {{t|scn|fimminaru|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|despicable person}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|koira}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|houndfish}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|en|harass}}From {{inh|en|enm|hounden}}, from the noun (see above).\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To persistently [[harass]] doggedly.\n#: {{syn|en|badger|bait|Thesaurus:pester}}\n#: {{ux|en|He '''hounded''' me for weeks, but I was simply unable to pay back his loan.}}\n#* {{quote-web\n|en\n|date=2019-04-11\n|author=Marcel Theroux\n|title=Machines Like Me by Ian McEwan review – intelligent mischief\n|work=The Guardian\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/apr/11/machines-like-me-by-ian-mcewan-review\n|passage=More pertinently for the plot, another marked difference from history is that the United Kingdom of this 1982 is precociously computerised. Instead of having been '''hounded''' to death for his homosexuality, the scientist Alan Turing is thriving and lauded.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[urge]] on against; to set (dogs) upon in hunting.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1897|author=Andrew Lang|title=The Book of Dreams and Ghosts|page=162\n|passage=We both thought we saw what had the appearance to be a fox, and '''hounded''' the dogs at it, but they would not pursue it.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|hound down\n|unhounded\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to persistently harass}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+check|bg|измъчвам}}, {{t+check|bg|тормозя}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|nahánět|impf}}, {{t|cs|pronásledovat|impf}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|vainota}}\n* German: {{t+|de|belästigen}}, {{t+|de|nachstellen}}, {{t+|de|verfolgen}}, {{t+|de|jagen}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|hundse}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пресле́довать}}, {{t+|ru|трави́ть}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to urge on against}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|usuttaa}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*ḱewh₁-}}\n{{etymid|en|bar}}From {{inh|en|enm|hownde}}, {{m|enm|hount}}, {{m|enm|houn}}, probably from {{der|en|non|húnn}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*hūnaz}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|en|hune}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|nautical|in the plural}} [[projection|Projections]] located at the [[masthead]] or [[foremast]], serving as a support for the [[trestletree]]s and top on which to rest; a [[foretop]].\n# A side [[bar]] used to strengthen portions of the running gear of a vehicle.\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=dhnou|Duhon|Hudon|hundo|no duh}}\n\n{{C|en|Hunting dogs|People|Stock characters}}\n\n==Middle English==\n[[File:Viljo koirarannalla 11.jpg|thumb|{{uxi|enm|an '''hound''' in watres|a '''dog''' in water}}]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|enm|honde|hounde|hund|hunde|hond|hownd|hownde|hwond}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|enm|:inh|ang:hund<id:dog>}}\nFrom {{inh|enm|ang|hund}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*hund}}, in turn from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*hundaz}}. Ultimately descended from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*ḱwṓ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|enm|/huːnd/|/hund/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{enm-noun|houndes|pl2=hounden|pl2_qual=rare|dat=hounde}}\n\n# [[dog]], {{l|en|hound}} {{gloss|The canid {{taxfmt|Canis lupus familiaris|subspecies}}}}\n## A [[pet]] dog; a dog kept for [[companionship]].\n## A [[hunting]] or [[sporting]] dog; a hound.\n## {{lb|enm|specifically}} A [[male]] or fully-[[grown]] dog.\n# {{n-g|A strong term of abuse, especially used against enemies of one's religion}}\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} A [[heraldic]] portrayal of a dog.\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} The [[forces]] of evil; the [[infernal]] army.\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} [[Sirius]] {{gloss|star}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nThe general word for \"dog\" is ''hound''; {{m|enm|dogge}} is vaguely derogatory and has a sense of \"mongrel\" or \"cur\".\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|enm|hound fysch}}\n* {{l|enm|hounden}}\n* {{l|enm|houndesberye}}\n* {{l|enm|houndestonge}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|en|hound}}\n** Northumbrian: [[hoond]], [[hund]]\n* {{desc|sco|hoond|hund}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=hǒund |pos=n |id=MED21338 |accessdate=2018-06-11}}\n\n{{cln|enm|derogatory terms|weak nouns}}\n{{C|enm|Dogs|Male animals|Mammals|Religion|Stars}}"}}